sublevels.theory:
C++ uses stream objects from `<fstream>` to read/write files.

```cpp
#include <fstream>

// Write to file
std::ofstream outFile("data.txt");
outFile << "Hello, file!\n";
outFile.close();

// Read from file
std::ifstream inFile("data.txt");
std::string line;
while (std::getline(inFile, line)) {
    std::cout << line << '\n';
}
```

- `std::ofstream` — output file stream (write)
- `std::ifstream` — input file stream (read)
- `std::fstream` — both read and write
- Always check if file opened successfully: `if (!inFile) { ... }`
- Always close files (or use RAII — the destructor closes them)

**Binary file I/O:**
```cpp
std::ofstream bin("data.bin", std::ios::binary);
int x = 12345;
bin.write(reinterpret_cast<char*>(&x), sizeof(x));
```

**`std::stringstream`** — in-memory stream:
```cpp
std::stringstream ss;
ss << "value: " << 42;
std::string result = ss.str();
```

**Seek/tell:**
- `file.seekg(pos)` — reposition read position
- `file.tellg()` — get current read position
- `file.seekp(pos)` — reposition write position
- Offset flags: `std::ios::beg`, `std::ios::cur`, `std::ios::end`

**Memory-mapped files** — map file contents directly to process address space for high-performance I/O (using OS APIs like `mmap` or `CreateFileMapping`).

**C++23 `std::print` to file:** `std::print(outFile, "val={}", x);`

**`<filesystem>` (C++17):** portable file system operations:
```cpp
#include <filesystem>
namespace fs = std::filesystem;
fs::path p = "data/output.txt";
fs::create_directories(p.parent_path());
for (auto& entry : fs::directory_iterator(".")) {
    std::cout << entry.path() << '\n';
}
```

**Buffered vs unbuffered I/O:** `std::ios::sync_with_stdio(false)` decouples C and C++ streams for performance.
